sec.p:
[1] XGBoost Regressor: The XGBoost algorithm favors having a solid and efficient artificial intelligence environment and is among the most popularly chosen machine learning algorithms in supervised learning, generally regression, and classification. XGBoost here would be used to try to predict the RUL (remaining useful life) of an EV battery. The RUL is learned given the working parameters such as charge cycles, voltage thresholds, and discharge time of the battery. One particular advantage that might give an edge at times is the fact that it can accept datasets with missing data, which makes it a suitable candidate for some real-world battery data, where some feature recordings might be incomplete. XGBoost creates an ensemble of decision trees such that each new tree is fit to minimize the residual errors of those that preceded it so that the accuracy of the ensemble can be improved. This ensemble's accuracy is further improved on an iterative basis by gradient boosting. Hyperparameter optimization is crucial to XGBoost achieving the best results; parameters are tuned such as learning rate, max depth of trees, and number estimator to achieve the best value for accuracy. With the capability of XGBoost to perform well on big data, it can describe the complexities and variant nature of EV battery data.
\begin{equation*}
\hat{y}=\sum_{k=1}^{K} f_{k}(x)
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

Stacking is a classical ensemble learning approach with an intent to boost prediction accuracy by averaging or combining different regression methods. In the project, the Stacking Regressor aggregates the predictions from the XGBoost, Random Forest, and KNN models with the premise that base models are trained and predicted on an input set, and their predictions are used as new features of the meta-model, usually linear regression, to predict the final output. It unveils diverse patterns in data, hence mitigating bias and variance against each other. Since stacking tends to fuse two models that predict RUL in complementary fashions, at the end of the day, this PM is meant to end up better battery management and proper replacement planning for EV batteries.
\begin{equation*}
\hat{y}=\sum_{k=1}^{K} f_{k}(x)
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

Being an ensemble method, the Voting Regressor makes a bag of predictions from as many regression models as possible. Through this project, it combines RUL predictions generated by the XGBoost, Random Forest, and KNN models. By taking the mean of the constituent models" outputs, the Voting Regressor maintains a set of balanced predictions so as not to rely on one single model. This will grant a much better ability to generalize and limit each individual model from its drawbacks. A Voting Regressor will be able to provide real-time RUL predictions in the battery swapping outlets so that the prices are set fairly and the batteries are better managed.
\begin{equation*}
y=\frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^{N} y_{i}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
